<div class="explanation">
    <h2>⚠️ Why "The GC Isn't Working" Is the Wrong Diagnosis</h2>

    <p>
        When a dashboard widget's memory grows over time, the instinctive blame is the Garbage Collector.
        This is almost always incorrect. JavaScript engines ship battle-tested GC implementations.
        The real culprit is nearly always <strong style="color:var(--accent-red)">live references that prevent the GC from ever
        seeing the objects as collectible in the first place</strong>.
    </p>

    <h3>🔴 What the Buggy Version Does Wrong</h3>
    <div class="two-col">
        <div>
            <div class="code-block"><code>
<span class="cmt">// ❌ BUGGY — references never released</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="fn">BuggyDashboard</span> {
  <span class="fn">constructor</span>() {
    <span class="cmt">// These arrays grow forever.</span>
    <span class="cmt">// Removing a widget from the DOM</span>
    <span class="cmt">// does NOT remove it from here.</span>
    <span class="kw">this</span>.widgetRegistry  = [];
    <span class="kw">this</span>.domReferences   = [];
    <span class="kw">this</span>.listenerHandles = [];
    <span class="kw">this</span>.dataCache       = {};
    <span class="kw">this</span>.intervalIds     = [];
  }

  <span class="fn">addWidget</span>(id) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> el = <span class="fn">createElement</span>(id);

    <span class="cmt">// Store DOM node — prevents GC</span>
    <span class="kw">this</span>.domReferences.<span class="fn">push</span>(el);

    <span class="cmt">// Anonymous listener — can't removeEventListener</span>
    <span class="kw">const</span> handler = () => <span class="fn">onUpdate</span>(id);
    el.<span class="fn">addEventListener</span>(<span class="str">'click'</span>, handler);
    <span class="cmt">// handler reference is lost! ☠</span>

    <span class="cmt">// Interval keeps widget data alive</span>
    <span class="kw">const</span> iv = <span class="fn">setInterval</span>(() => {
      <span class="kw">this</span>.dataCache[id] = <span class="fn">fetchData</span>();
    }, <span class="num">1000</span>);
    <span class="kw">this</span>.intervalIds.<span class="fn">push</span>(iv); <span class="cmt">// never cleared</span>

    <span class="kw">this</span>.widgetRegistry.<span class="fn">push</span>({ id, el });
  }

  <span class="fn">removeWidget</span>(id) {
    el.<span class="fn">remove</span>(); <span class="cmt">// DOM removed ✓</span>
    <span class="cmt">// But widgetRegistry, domReferences,</span>
    <span class="cmt">// dataCache, intervalIds still hold</span>
    <span class="cmt">// strong refs → GC CANNOT collect. ✗</span>
  }
}
            </code></div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <ul>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-red)">DOM references</strong> stored in an array that is never pruned — the element cannot be GC'd even after <code>el.remove()</code>.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-red)">Anonymous event listeners</strong> capture <code>this</code> and widget data in their closure; without the original function reference, <code>removeEventListener</code> is impossible.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-red)">setInterval callbacks</strong> hold a closure over the widget object and keep the interval running after the widget is gone — a classic "detached closure" leak.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-red)">Data cache</strong> entries keyed by widget ID are never deleted, growing the object indefinitely.</li>
                <li>None of these are GC bugs. The GC correctly refuses to collect objects that are still reachable via a strong reference chain.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h3>🟢 What the Fixed Version Does Right</h3>
    <div class="two-col">
        <div>
            <div class="code-block"><code>
<span class="cmt">// ✅ FIXED — explicit cleanup on removal</span>
<span class="kw">class</span> <span class="fn">FixedDashboard</span> {
  <span class="fn">constructor</span>() {
    <span class="cmt">// Map keyed by id — easy targeted deletion</span>
    <span class="kw">this</span>.widgets = <span class="kw">new</span> <span class="fn">Map</span>();
  }

  <span class="fn">addWidget</span>(id) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> el = <span class="fn">createElement</span>(id);

    <span class="cmt">// Named handler — can be removed later</span>
    <span class="kw">const</span> handler = () => <span class="fn">onUpdate</span>(id);
    el.<span class="fn">addEventListener</span>(<span class="str">'click'</span>, handler);

    <span class="cmt">// Interval stored per-widget</span>
    <span class="kw">const</span> iv = <span class="fn">setInterval</span>(() => {
      entry.data = <span class="fn">fetchData</span>();
    }, <span class="num">1000</span>);

    <span class="cmt">// Single source of truth</span>
    <span class="kw">this</span>.widgets.<span class="fn">set</span>(id, { el, handler, iv });
  }

  <span class="fn">removeWidget</span>(id) {
    <span class="kw">const</span> entry = <span class="kw">this</span>.widgets.<span class="fn">get</span>(id);
    <span class="kw">if</span> (!entry) <span class="kw">return</span>;

    <span class="cmt">// 1. Stop the interval</span>
    <span class="fn">clearInterval</span>(entry.iv);

    <span class="cmt">// 2. Remove the named listener</span>
    entry.el.<span class="fn">removeEventListener</span>(<span class="str">'click'</span>, entry.handler);

    <span class="cmt">// 3. Remove from DOM</span>
    entry.el.<span class="fn">remove</span>();

    <span class="cmt">// 4. Drop the Map entry → GC can now</span>
    <span class="cmt">// collect el, handler, data ✓</span>
    <span class="kw">this</span>.widgets.<span class="fn">delete</span>(id);
  }
}
            </code></div>
        </div>
        <div>
            <ul>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-green)">Named handler references</strong> stored alongside each widget so <code>removeEventListener</code> can be called with the exact same function object.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-green)">clearInterval</strong> called before the widget is discarded, severing the closure and stopping background work.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-green)">Map.delete(id)</strong> removes the last strong reference to the widget entry — the GC can now collect the element, handler, and all associated data.</li>
                <li><strong style="color:var(--accent-green)">No parallel arrays</strong> that could get out of sync; a single <code>Map</code> is the authoritative registry.</li>
                <li>After removal, the object is <em>truly unreachable</em> — this is all the GC needs.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h3>🔬 The Reference-Chain Mental Model</h3>
    <p>
        The GC uses a <strong>mark-and-sweep</strong> algorithm. Starting from "GC roots"
        (global variables, the call stack, active closures), it marks every reachable object.
        Anything <em>not</em> marked is swept. An object is collectible
        <strong>if and only if no reachable root holds a path to it</strong>.
    </p>
    <div class="code-block"><code>
<span class="cmt">// Buggy reference chain — GC root still reaches removed widget</span>
window.buggyDashboard  →  .domReferences[ ]  →  widgetElement  →  ❌ NOT collected
window.buggyDashboard  →  .listenerHandles[ ] →  closureData   →  ❌ NOT collected
window.buggyDashboard  →  .intervalIds[ ]    →  (running timer) → ❌ NOT collected

<span class="cmt">// Fixed reference chain — after removeWidget()</span>
window.fixedDashboard  →  .widgets Map  →  (entry deleted)  →  ✅ GC can collect
<span class="cmt">// widgetElement, handler, data are now unreachable → swept</span>
    </code></div>

    <h3>📋 Common Memory Leak Patterns in Dashboards</h3>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Anonymous event listeners</strong> — always store the handler reference if you need to remove it.</li>
        <li><strong>setInterval / setTimeout</strong> — always call <code>clearInterval</code>/<code>clearTimeout</code> in your cleanup path.</li>
        <li><strong>Global / module-level caches</strong> — use <code>WeakMap</code> when keys are objects, or explicitly delete stale entries.</li>
        <li><strong>Closure captures</strong> — a callback that closes over a large object keeps that object alive for its entire lifetime.</li>
        <li><strong>Third-party library subscriptions</strong> — charting libs, pub/sub buses, reactive stores — always call their <code>destroy()</code> / <code>unsubscribe()</code> APIs.</li>
        <li><strong>Detached DOM trees</strong> — <code>el.remove()</code> only removes from the live tree; if you keep a JS reference the node (and its subtree) stays in memory.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="verdict">
        <strong>Verdict:</strong> The Garbage Collector is working perfectly in both versions.
        In the buggy version it simply has nothing to collect — every widget object is still
        reachable through a live reference chain anchored to the dashboard instance.
        The fix is not to "force GC" but to <strong>break the reference chain</strong> by
        removing listeners, clearing timers, and deleting registry entries when a widget is
        destroyed. Once those strong references are gone, the GC will reclaim the memory
        at its next cycle without any further intervention.
    </div>
</div>

