---

## How to Use It

| Action | What to observe |
|---|---|
| **Add widgets** on both sides | Buggy: all three counters climb. Fixed: only "Live Widgets" climbs |
| **Remove widgets** on the buggy side | Live count drops but **Leaked Refs stays high** — the red bar keeps growing |
| **Remove widgets** on the fixed side | All counters drop back to zero — the green bar stays flat |
| **Stress ×10** | Rapidly add/remove 10 widgets — the leak gap becomes very obvious on the chart |
| **Clear All** | Buggy: DOM empties but leaked ref count **remains** — Fixed: everything resets to zero |

---

## Why the GC Diagnosis is Wrong — Summary

```
GC Root → buggyDashboard.domReferences[n] → widgetElement  ← GC sees this as LIVE
GC Root → buggyDashboard.intervalIds[n]   → running timer  ← GC sees this as LIVE

GC Root → fixedDashboard.widgets          → (entry deleted) ← GC sees NOTHING → collects
```

The GC is doing its job **correctly** in both cases. It cannot collect an object that is still reachable. The fix is never to "force GC" — it is to **break the reference chain** by calling `clearInterval`, `removeEventListener`, and `Map.delete()` before discarding a widget.

