<h1>🔍 Memory Leak Demo: The GC Is Not Broken</h1>
<p class="subtitle">
  Your colleague blames the garbage collector — but the real culprit is <strong>unreleased references</strong>.
</p>

<!-- ── Explainer ── -->
<div class="explainer">
  <h2>⚠️ Why "the GC isn't working" is almost always wrong</h2>
  <p>
    JavaScript's garbage collector <strong>cannot free memory that is still reachable</strong>.
    When you remove a widget from the DOM but forget to clean up its event listeners or store
    its DOM node in a JavaScript array/closure, the GC sees a live reference and correctly
    keeps the object alive. <strong>The GC is doing exactly its job.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    The three classic leak patterns shown here:
    &nbsp;<code>addEventListener</code> without a matching <code>removeEventListener</code>,
    &nbsp;storing removed DOM nodes in a global <code>widgetRegistry</code> array,
    &nbsp;and interval/timer callbacks that capture widget references — all prevent
    collection because <em>your code</em> is holding the references, not a GC bug.
  </p>
  <p>
    The fix is simple: <strong>explicitly release every reference</strong> when a widget is
    destroyed — remove listeners, nullify stored nodes, and clear timers.
  </p>
</div>

