## What this demo shows

### The core misconception
When someone says "the GC isn't collecting my widgets," they're actually describing correct GC behavior. The GC **cannot** collect an object that still has live references pointing to it — and that's exactly what leaked listeners create.

### Three leak sources per widget (buggy version)
| Source | Why it leaks |
|---|---|
| `setInterval` | The timer callback closes over `widget`; the timer queue is a GC root |
| `document.addEventListener('mousemove', ...)` | `document` is a GC root; it holds the listener; the listener closes over `widget` |
| `window.addEventListener('resize', ...)` | Same chain through `window` |

### Why the fix works
The fixed version stores **named references** to every handler and every timer ID on the widget object itself. Before DOM removal, it calls `clearInterval` and `removeEventListener` with those exact references, severing all three retention chains. Once no GC root can reach the widget, the collector is free to reclaim it.

### What to watch in the demo
- Hit **Stress ×10** on the buggy panel repeatedly — leaked listeners and zombie timers climb without bound
- Do the same on the fixed panel — both counters stay permanently at zero
- The memory meter visualizes the growing retained-object graph on the left vs. the flat line on the right

