  <div class="gc-myth">
    <h4>🔮 Why Blaming the GC Is Almost Always Wrong</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>GC rule #1:</strong> An object is collected only when no reachable reference points to it. If memory grows, something reachable is holding on.</li>
      <li><strong>Event listeners are roots:</strong> A listener registered on <code>document</code>, <code>window</code>, or any long-lived element keeps its entire closure — and every object the closure captures — alive forever.</li>
      <li><strong>Closures capture, not copy:</strong> When your handler closes over a widget node, it holds a <em>live reference</em> to that node. Removing the node from the DOM doesn't break the reference.</li>
      <li><strong>Registries and caches are common culprits:</strong> Any plain object used as a map (<code>{}</code>) or a regular <code>Array</code> will prevent GC. Use <code>WeakMap</code> / <code>WeakRef</code> when you don't want to own the lifetime.</li>
      <li><strong>The GC is not slow or lazy:</strong> Modern engines run incremental, generational GC. If it hasn't collected something, it's because it <em>can't</em> — not because it hasn't gotten around to it.</li>
