## Why the GC Diagnosis is Categorically Wrong

Here's the complete breakdown:

### The Reference Chain the GC Sees

```
Window (root)
  └── leakedWidgetRegistry (global array)
        └── widgetObj  ← still reachable!
              ├── .domNode  (detached DOM node) ← still reachable!
              └── [anonymous listener closures] ← still reachable!
```

**The GC traces from roots. Everything reachable from a root is live.** It cannot collect `widgetObj` because your registry holds it. It's not a bug — it's the GC working exactly as designed.

### The Three Actual Causes

| Cause | Why It Leaks | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Anonymous listener closures | No reference saved = impossible to call `removeEventListener` | Use named functions, store the reference |
| Listeners capture widget object | Closure scope keeps entire `widgetObj` graph alive | `removeEventListener` before DOM removal |
| Registry never cleaned | Global array holds strong references to detached nodes | `registry.delete(id)` on widget removal |

### Why "Modern GCs Handle This" is Also Wrong

Modern engines use **mark-and-sweep**, not reference counting. They trace from GC roots (globals, stack frames, browser internals). Your registry **is** a GC root. The listener table inside the browser **is** a GC root. Both paths lead to your "deleted" widget. The GC marks it live on every cycle. It will never be collected until you break the reference chain yourself.

### The Bonus Problem Nobody Mentions

Leaked listeners **still fire**. Every `mousemove` over where that widget used to be (if another element is there) can still trigger the old handler, mutating state on objects you believe are deleted. This is ghost state corruption on top of the memory leak.
